         b'\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article id="post-508" class="post-508'
         b' post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncat'
         b'egorized">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 cla'
         b'ss="entry-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/what-makes-a-st'
         b'rong-researcher/" title="Permalink to What makes a strong researcher'
         b'?" rel="bookmark">What makes a strong researcher?</a></h1>\n\t'
         b'\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="s'
         b'ep">Posted on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/what-makes-'
         b'a-strong-researcher/" title="9:57 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="en'
         b'try-date" datetime="2012-04-17T21:57:39+00:00" pubdate>April 17, 201'
         b'2</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <'
         b'span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs'
         b'.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucaceyl/" title="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="'
         b'author">Emmanuel</a></span></span>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n'
         b'\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div c'
         b'lass="entry-content">\n\t\t\t<p>I was flipping through Simon Reynold'
         b's latest book &#8220;<em>Retromania: Pop Culture&#8217;s Addiction t'
         b'o its Own Past</em>&#8221; when this paragraph caught my eyes.</'
         b'p>\n<blockquote><p>According to Harold Bloom&#8217;s theory of cr'
         b'eativity, outlined in books like The Anxiety of Influence and A Map '
         b'of Misreading, a &#8216;strong&#8217; poet is one who&#8217;s heavil'
         b'y influenced by a predecessor but who resists that influence, fights'
         b' it with every ounce of its strength. In Bloom&#8217;s Freudian-myst'
         b'ical account, the resulting Oedipal struggle entails the younger poe'
         b't (who will have been initiated, turned on to the glory of poetry by'
         b' a primal encounter with the elder&#8217;s work) swerving from the a'
         b'ncestor&#8217;s style, willfully misreading it or doing violence to '
         b'it in some other way. The strong artist is impelled by a despairing '
         b'sense of belatedness, the feeling that nothing new can be said becau'
         b'se the precursor said it all. A titanic psychological struggle to se'
         b'lf-birth oneself as an artist is required before the descendant ceas'
         b'es to ventriloquise the dead elder and finds his own voice. But a &#'
         b'8216;weak&#8217; poet (or painter or musician) is simply inundated, '
         b'flooded by the ancestor&#8217;s vision.</p></blockquote>\n<p>Does'
         b' this theory about creativity applies to research? Is a strong resea'
         b'rcher one who&#8217;s been heavily influenced by predecessor&#8217;s'
         b' work and makes violence to it to find his or her own voice? I belie'
         b've there&#8217;s some truth in this. I do not mean that software eng'
         b'ineering research should be like poetry. I&#8217;m with Bertand Russ'
         b'ell, I like <a title="Bertrand Russell - Clarity and exact thinking"'
         b' href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mpJcn0Otk7I">clarity and exact'
         b' thinking</a>. There are nevertheless strong parallels between creat'
         b'ivity in research, poetry, and in fact most other kinds of creative '
         b'work. All require some form of obsession with your work, and an urge'
         b' to explore the unknown and move things forward.</p>\n<p>I cannot'
         b' finish this without some poetry. So here&#8217;s\xc2\xa0<a title='
         b'"Niall Spooner-Harvey" href="http://www.whippersnapperpress.com/arch'
         b'ives/writer/niall-spooner-harvey">Niall Spooner-Harvey</a>, one of L'
         b'ondon&#8217;s finest contemporary poets, and his already classic &#8'
         b'220;All My Conversvatories Have Won Awards&#8221;.</p>\n<p><span '
         b"class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:center; display: block;'><if"
         b"rame class='youtube-player' type='text/html' width='584' height='359"
         b"' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/N7RAbdHr78A?version=3&#038;rel=1"
         b'&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#'
         b"038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0'></iframe></span></p>\n<p>&"
         b'nbsp;</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<foote'
